<p id="fs-id1170572511239">For the following problems, evaluate the limit using the squeeze theorem. Use a calculator to graph the functions <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>f</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> when possible.</p>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1170572511282">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1170572511284">
<p id="fs-id1170572511286"><strong data-effect="bold">[T]</strong> True or False? If <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8804;</mo><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>&#8804;</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#8804;</mo><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>&#8804;</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> then <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></munder><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></munder><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1170572511389">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1170572511391">
<p id="fs-id1170572511393"><strong data-effect="bold">[T]</strong> <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>&#952;</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></munder><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mtext>cos</mtext><mspace width="0.1em"/><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#952;</mi></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>&#952;</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></munder><msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mtext>cos</mtext><mspace width="0.1em"/><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#952;</mi></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></p>
</div>
<div data-type="solution" id="fs-id1170571625942">
<p id="fs-id1170571625945">The limit is zero.<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
</p><span data-type="media" id="fs-id1170571625949" data-alt="The graph of three functions over the domain [-1,1], colored red, green, and blue as follows: red: theta^2, green: theta^2 * cos (1/theta), and blue: - (theta^2). The red and blue functions open upwards and downwards respectively as parabolas with vertices at the origin. The green function is trapped between the two.">
<img src="/resources/29107ec9cb983350dfd0403485093c3393463387/CNX_Calc_Figure_02_03_206.jpg" data-media-type="image/jpeg" alt="The graph of three functions over the domain [-1,1], colored red, green, and blue as follows: red: theta^2, green: theta^2 * cos (1/theta), and blue: - (theta^2). The red and blue functions open upwards and downwards respectively as parabolas with vertices at the origin. The green function is trapped between the two."/>
</span>
</div>
